The definition of `fun_restrict` is `fun x => if x ‚ąą A then g x else v` where `g` is `fun_extend f v`.

So `fun_restrict (fun_extend f v) A x` is `if x ‚ąą A then (fun_extend f v) x else v`.

The goal is `if x ‚ąą A then (fun_extend f v) x else v = f x`.

We can simplify this by noting that if `x ‚ąą A`, then `(fun_extend f v) x = f x`, so the left side becomes `f x`. If `x ‚ąČ A`, then the left side is `v`, but the right side is `f x`. This would mean `v = f x`, which is not necessarily true.

Wait, this suggests that the equality is only true when `x ‚ąą A`. But in Lean, `fun_restrict` is a function `‚ÜĎA ‚Üí V`, so `x` is implicitly an element of `‚ÜĎA`, which means `x ‚ąą A`.

